</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   NLI
</CO>
<IN>
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   HICKSVILLE, N.Y. -- Citing weak sales of weather-related
air conditioning products, Newmark &amp; Lewis Inc. reported a
60% decline in net income for the fiscal second quarter ended
July 31 to $552,000, or nine cents a share, from $1.4
million, or 22 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 31%
to $90.3 million from $69.1 million.
   The second quarter includes results for the former Brick
Church Appliance Inc., a New Jersey-based chain of appliance
and electronics stores acquired by Newmark &amp; Lewis in May.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the six months, the discount appliance and electronics
retailer had a net loss of $594,000, or 10 cents a share,
compared with net income of $853,000, or 14 cents a share, a
year ago. Sales rose 20% to $142.5 million from $118.7
million.
   Liquidation of Brick Church's inventories boosted sales
but also lowered profit margins, contributing to the decline
in net income, a company spokesman said.
