<HL>
   Union Camp to Buy Bag Maker
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   UCC
</CO>
<IN>
CONTAINERS &amp; PACKAGING, BAGS, CANS, BOXES (CTR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WAYNE, N.J. -- Union Camp Corp., a paper, packaging and
chemical concern, said it will acquire all the stock of Chase
Packaging Corp., an Old Greenwich, Conn., maker of bags for
agricultural and chemical uses and laminated specialty bags,
for about $86 million.
   Under the agreement, Union Camp will pay $330 a common
share and $107 a preferred share of Chase Packaging. Holders
of Chase Packaging common may choose Union Camp common stock
or cash in exchange for their shares. Trading on the pink
sheets, Chase's common was quoted Friday at $200 to $225.
Francis H. Luddigton, sole trustee of family trusts that
together own 55% of Chase Packaging, said the trusts support
the transaction and will elect to take Union Camp stock.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In 1989, Chase Packaging earned $6.9 million on sales of
$183 million. Union Camp had 1989 profit of $299 million on
sales of $2.8 billion.
</TEXT>
