<HL>
   Government Wants to Change S&amp;L Sales
   That Gave $4.2 Billion in Tax Benefits
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The government wants to alter roughly 200
controversial thrift sales that bestowed about $4.2 billion
in tax benefits on wealthy buyers in 1988, but it's unlikely
the cash-strapped savings and loan cleanup agency can take
action any time soon.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Moreover, financier Ronald Perelman, who struck the
sweetest deal with $1.8 billion in tax benefits alone, also
secured the most ironclad transaction, with fewest government
options within the contract to reduce costs.
   For more than six hours Friday, former S&amp;L regulators
defended the sales before the House Banking Committee, saying
that the sales, conducted in an atmosphere of urgency in late
1988 before tax benefits were to expire, were the best they
could do in dire circumstances.
   Hundreds of thrifts were insolvent, and the S&amp;L insurance
fund was broke. To attract buyers for the institutions, the
regulators gave them high-interest bearing notes and other
assistance to compensate for the money-losing assets in the
sick thrifts. "When you have an imposed deadline, no cash and
doubtful credit, you are going to pay through the nose," said
William Seidman, the head of the Resolution Trust Corp.,
which runs the S&amp;L cleanup. "I would say the real question is
whether they should have undertaken the transactions at all."
   Now, regulators are combing through the agreements,
looking for ways to reduce costs without breaking the
contracts. Such options include paying off the notes, or
buying the thrift assets and managing them at lower costs.
   Mr. Seidman said that a study of the 1988 thrift deals by
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. will be released
tomorrow, but that he expects final costs to have risen to
$54 billion on a present value basis from $39 billion,
because of poor assumptions by the thrift regulators, as well
as declining values in real estate held by the thrifts. A
House Banking Committee study pegged the costs at $71
billion.
   Exercising those options requires huge piles of cash, up
front. Hence, Larry White, a former thrift regulator who
helped structure the deals, projected that the government
could save $6.4 billion over eight years by prepaying the
notes alone. But the RTC doesn't currently have the $25
billion required to buy back the notes in the first place.
The S&amp;L cleanup funding is part of the federal budget talks
between Congress and the Bush administration.
   Even if the cleanup agency had the liquidity, in the case
of Mr. Perelman it doesn't have the contractual right.
According to a House Banking Committee study, the Perelman
acquisition of five thrifts, now known as First Gibraltar,
Houston, received $2.3 billion in tax-free notes. The first
$865 million can't be prepaid for five years; as for the
rest, the holder is protected against loss in case of
repayment.
   Even so, a spokesman for MacAndrews &amp; Forbes Holdings
Inc., Mr. Perelman's New York-based company, said he believed
some government costs might be trimmed from the transaction.
"Within the four corners of our deal, there is room for some
cost-savings," he said, but he didn't know by how much. "A
wholesale renegotiation isn't foreseeable," he said.
   Mr. Perelman is still buying up thrifts, even though the
S&amp;L cleanup law, passed last year, explicitly barred any of
the 1988 buyers from acquiring other thrifts with government
assistance. But that rule was scrapped because so few bidders
have sought the S&amp;Ls. Just Friday, First Gibraltar acquired
Sooner Federal Savings &amp; Loan, a $1.2 billion-asset Tulsa,
Okla., thrift. And previously it acquired $2.6 billion San
Antonio Savings Association. Both are operated separately
from First Gibraltar.
   Mr. Seidman said regulators are also trying to determine
if there is a legal basis for voiding thrift sales. So far,
they haven't found one, he said.
   Details of the transactions infuriated the committee.
Members complained that the Robert Bass Group was given the
exclusive right to bid for American Savings Bank, Stockton,
Calif., for more than six months, a decision Mr. White said
he regretted. The panel was also outraged that the wealthy
Caroline Hunt Trust Estate, Dallas, was released from an
agreement to keep its Southwest Savings Association, Dallas,
well-capitalized.
   "Frankly, these make the average citizen question very
seriously the intents and capabilities of the U.S.
government, if not its integrity," said Rep. Jim Leach (R.,
Iowa.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Souter's Position on Key Issues Remains
   An Enigma as Senate Hearings Progress
   ----
   By Stephen Wermiel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Although Senate confirmation hearings for
David Souter may last two or three more days, there appears
to be little doubt that the New Hampshire judge is poised to
take a seat on the U.S. Supreme Court.
   But his deft testimony has caused senators, liberal and
conservative interest groups, and lawyers to wonder where he
will sit on the high court's spectrum of legal views.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Based on his 10 hours of interrogation thus far, he
appears likely to fit in the court's ideological middle -- a
moderately conservative spot occupied most often by Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor.
   On at least two issues -- when the government must
accommodate religious practices and how to decide what rights
the guarantee of "due process" protects -- Judge Souter
rejected the views of the court's most ardent conservative,
Justice Antonin Scalia, and said he prefers the approach of
Justice O'Connor.
   This may upset some conservatives, who hope Judge Souter
will be a staunch ally for Justice Scalia and Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist. During questioning Friday, conservative
Republican Sens. Charles Grassley of Iowa and Gordon Humphrey
of New Hampshire seemed flustered when some of Judge Souter's
answers fell short of dogmatic conservative responses.
   Conservatives have been disappointed in the failure of a
solid majority to coalesce on issues such as abortion,
religious freedom and affirmative action. The court has moved
in a more conservative direction on these issues, usually by
5-4 margins, but the five-vote majority frequently has been
splintered, with Justice O'Connor and, sometimes, Justices
Anthony M. Kennedy and Byron R. White reaching the same
results but following different legal reasoning.
   The more solid four-vote liberal wing of Justices Thurgood
Marshall, Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens, long led
by Justice William J. Brennan Jr., was sometimes able to take
advantage of conservative differences to secure a fifth vote
for a majority. Justice Brennan's retirement on July 20,
creating the vacancy for which Judge Souter was nominated,
will make it much tougher for the liberal wing to obtain a
majority.
   But the question remains whether the conservative majority
will become any more cohesive once Judge Souter, a former New
Hampshire Supreme Court justice who turned 51 years old
today, joins their ranks.
   It is difficult to predict the performance of Supreme
Court justices, since most justices say it takes them five
years to really learn the job and since some of their views
have changed once they were on the bench. Based on his own
testimony, however, Judge Souter shed some light on his
approach to a few important legal issues.
   Last April, in an opinion by Justice Scalia, the high
court ruled that Oregon may prohibit the use of the
hallucinogenic drug, peyote, by the Native American Church.
State laws that are applicable to everyone don't violate the
First Amendment guarantee of religious freedom, even when
they prohibit a religious ritual, Justice Scalia wrote,
saying the state needn't justify such interference.
   In a separate opinion, Justice O'Connor said Justice
Scalia's decision "dramatically departs" from
long-established First Amendment decisions that require the
state to have a strong justification for interfering with
religious practices.
   Judge Souter, although emphasizing that he wasn't making a
commitment, said he preferred Justice O'Connor's approach.
   In another instance, Justice Scalia wrote in a 1989
decision that the 14th Amendment guarantee of "due process"
protects those individual liberties that are rooted in
American history when examined only in the narrowest terms.
In a separate opinion, Justice O'Connor rejected such a
narrow role for history and tradition in defining civil
liberties. In his testimony on Friday, Judge Souter, too,
rejected such a narrow approach.
   In other developments in the hearings, which continue
today:
   -- Judge Souter said he would have an open mind with no
"agenda" on the question of whether to overrule Roe vs. Wade,
the 1973 decision that recognized the right to abortion.
   -- Abortion-rights groups announced their opposition to
him, since they want a nominee committed to upholding the
right.
   -- Judge Souter said affirmative action is necessary,
although he was careful not to commit himself in the
continuing debate over how far it may properly go. When
discrimination has been proven, he said, it isn't enough to
stop it. "The appropriate response is to say, `Undo it.'"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0084.
</DOCID>
