<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Cleveland Newspaper Loses
   Suit Brought by Promoters
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11
</SO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   CLEVELAND -- Plaintiffs won a $13.5 million libel suit in
Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Court against the Cleveland
Plain Dealer.
   Former promoters of a car race called the Budweiser
Cleveland Grand Prix alleged that they were defamed by
stories in the newspaper in 1984, and followed up in 1985 and
1986. The plaintiffs sought $16 million in damages, including
$10 million in punitive damages.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The $13.5 million verdict included $4.5 million in
compensatory damages and $9 million in punitive damages.
   A secretary for the paper's top news officials said the
Plain Dealer hadn't yet prepared a statement about the
verdict. Lawyers who represented the newspaper couldn't be
reached for comment.
   The articles said that Charles K. Newcomb and James H.
Foster had paid themselves nearly $1 million from race
proceeds for management fees, salaries, commissions, legal
and accounting fees, and equipment rental fees in violation
of the lease they had with the city, according to a story in
Thursday's Plain Dealer.
   Messrs. Newcomb and Foster and their company, C. K.
Newcomb &amp; Associates of Cleveland, sold the race to
businessman and former race car driver Roger Penske in 1985.
At that point the Plain Dealer became a co-sponsor.
   Plain Dealer lawyers had argued the articles were correct,
the newspaper reported. The Plain Dealer is part of the
Newhouse chain, which is owned by Advance Publications Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0032
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0032.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE U.S. IS EXPORTING more gasoline, even as debate
continues over the adequacy of the nation's future petroleum
supplies. Higher foreign gas prices are spurring the trend,
which could result in continued high costs for U.S. motorists
and tight wholesale supplies in the coming months. Those
factors in turn could create new policy problems for the
federal government.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GM and the UAW agreed to continue contract talks, working
past Friday's strike deadline. The union's move marked only
the second time ever that it put off a strike after the
expiration of a Big Three pact. In Canada, almost 13,000
workers at the Ford unit began a strike Saturday.
   ---
   GOP budget negotiators proposed a limit on all tax
deductions for taxpayers making more than $200,000 annually,
said top aides. The move was a response to a Democratic bid
to pair the capital-gains tax cut with higher income taxes on
the rich.
   ---
   Airlines are attempting to lift fares for the second time
since the Mideast conflict boosted fuel prices and created
the prospect of record industry losses. Several big carriers
said they plan to raise fares by 4.2%.
   ---
   A UAL union group is likely to abandon its most recent
$4.38 billion offer to acquire the airline company and is
considering making a lower offer, according to people
familiar with the group. The union group has ended its formal
alliance with New York investment firm Coniston Partners.
   ---
   The U.S. economy is clearly being hurt by rising oil
prices, according to the latest government economic reports.
In August, producer prices soared 1.3%, retail sales fell
0.6% and industrial output slipped 0.2%.
   ---
   Foreign investment in the U.S. is down sharply this year,
while American investment abroad is rising. Analysts warn
that these trends will bring the U.S. a weaker dollar, higher
interest rates and a slower economy.
   ---
   Stock prices fell on signs of growing Mideast tensions and
weakness in the U.S. economy. The Dow Jones industrials
dropped 18.56 to 2564.11.
   ---
   A First Gibraltar Bank affiliate acquired Oklahoma's
largest thrift, Sooner Federal S&amp;L of Tulsa.
   ---
   The Resolution Trust Corp. wants to alter roughly 200
controversial thrift sales that bestowed about $4.2 billion
in tax benefits on wealthy buyers in 1988, but it's unlikely
the cash-strapped S&amp;L cleanup agency can take action any time
soon.
   ---
   U.S. grain export subsidies have reached record levels, as
the Agriculture Department seeks to counter the competitive
challenge of the EC.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 133,390,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2564.11, off 18.56; transportation 889.42, off 8.69;
utilities 199.20, off 0.88.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3338.92,
off 18.61.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.29, up 0.14; spot
index 129.07, off 0.17.
   Dollar: 136.95 yen, up 0.75; 1.5710 marks, up 0.0033.
</TEXT>
