<HL>
   Trade Outlook: IMF Official Stresses
   Urgency in Uruguay Round Talks
   ----
   By John T. Norman
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST MDEST F.ABI FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A slowdown in world economic growth rates
and the situation created by the crisis in the Middle East
"make it all the more urgent" that the Uruguay Round of world
trade negotiations be successfully completed by late this
year, according to Michel Camdessus, managing director of the
International Monetary Fund.
   With finance ministers, central bankers and other
officials of industrial nations and developing countries
scheduled to gather in Washington late this week for the
joint annual meeting of the IMF and the World Bank, top
officials of both international agencies will be stressing
this issue, along with the need for other actions to offset
higher world oil prices and the "second-round" economic
impact of the Middle East crisis on developing nations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "If the concept of international community has any
meaning," says Mr. Camdessus, then the industrial countries
must intensify their efforts to achieve higher economic
growth rates than can be achieved without triggering an
acceleration of inflation.
   "In the trade area," the IMF official adds, "it is
essential that they open their markets further and strive for
more liberal trade and payments systems. Indeed, the recent
slowdown in world growth, together with the situation created
by the situation in the Middle East, make it all the more
urgent that the Uruguay Round negotiations be concluded
successfully."
   Mr. Camdessus made his comments at a meeting of a United
Nations group in Paris last week, where he also said the
current world economic outlook points to a further slowing of
growth rates and higher inflation rates during 1990 and 1991
in industrial countries and a worsening of the export
prospects for developing countries as a result of weaker
demand for their products in world markets.
   The IMF, in its annual report approved by its executive
directors who represent the 151 member nations of the
international agency, also said "stronger efforts are
urgently needed to counter protectionism and to foster a more
open trading system with transparent, predictable and
nondiscriminatory rules in order to sustain" an expansion of
world trade and provide markets for exports from the indebted
developing countries.
   ---
   EXPORT GROWTH: Both the IMF and the World Bank, in their
annual reports, noted that world trade, measured either by
volume or value terms, expanded by about 7.5% last year, down
from an unusually high 9% increase a year earlier. But
exports of developing countries as a group failed to achieve
such big gains.
   The World Bank said 1989 was the first year since 1985
that exports of developing countries as a group didn't expand
at a higher rate than the world average, and it noted that
shipments of manufactured goods by the major Asian exporters
"fell sharply" last year.
   Market shares for exports have been shifting, the IMF
said.
   "The volume of goods exported by the U.S. increased by
10.5% in 1989, the best performance among the major
industrial countries," the IMF said, adding that this raised
the U.S. share of total world trade, excluding oil, to 13.5%
from a low of 11.5% in 1987.
   Japan's share of world exports in 1989, the IMF said,
declined to 10% from a peak of 11.5% in 1986, while West
Germany, displaced by the U.S. as the top world exporter of
manufactured goods, held "steady" with about a 12.5% share of
nonoil exports in 1989.
   ---
   MAJOR WORLD EXPORTERS: According to the World Bank, 23
countries rank among the leading exporters; they accounted
for about 78.2% of all exports in 1989.
   The World Bank ranking, in order, of the major exporters
in terms of their market-shares for all types of exports last
year, is: U.S., West Germany, Japan, France, Britain, Italy,
Canada, Soviet Union, the Netherlands, Belgium-Luxembourg,
South Korea, China, Sweden, Switzerland, Singapore, Spain,
Australia, Mexico, Brazil, Austria, East Germany, Saudi
Arabia, and Denmark.
   The World Bank didn't include data on exports of Taiwan or
Hong Kong, both of which probably would have made the list if
their shares of world exports had been computed.
   ---
   CZECHOSLOVAKIAN TRADE: Legislation to reduce U.S. tariff
rates for imports from Czechoslovakia was expected to glide
through the U.S. Congress without much difficulty before the
final 1990 Capitol Hill adjournment next month.
   But the White House plan to extend similar
most-favored-nation treatment to imports from the Soviet
Union apparently won't be considered by the U.S. Congress
until next year.
   In Moscow, U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said
last week that Soviet officials told him that it would take
four to eight weeks for the Supreme Soviet legislative body
to complete action on a proposed law to liberalize Soviet
emigration policies.
   ---
   AIRBUS SUBSIDIES: U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills is
leading a high-ranking delegation of U.S. corporation
executives, bankers, labor leaders and farm group officials
to Geneva early this week to size up the prospects for
completing the Uruguay Round of world trade negotiations
later this year.
   Mrs. Hills also plans to visit Brussels and Rome before
returning to Washington at the end of the week.
   During the Brussels visit, Mrs. Hills probably will also
hold talks with European Community Commissioner Frans
Andriessen on a proposed agreement that would limit
development subsidies provided to Airbus Industrie, the
western European commercial aircraft-building consortium, by
the governments of West Germany, Britain, France and Spain.
   U.S. and EC sources say prospects are improving that such
an agreement can be reached by the end of this month.
   ---
   PRIVATE INVESTMENTS IN THIRD WORLD: The International
Finance Corp., a World Bank affiliate that started off on a
small scale way back in 1956 to help finance manufacturing
plants and other private business ventures in developing
nations has become a relatively "big-money" operation.
   In the year ending last June 30, for example, the IFC made
about $2.2 billion in such investments and it persuaded
international commercial banks to provide about $622 million
of that amount through participations in the IFC-approved
loans and equity investments.
   Now the IFC is looking for its 135-member countries to
agree late this year on a $1 billion IFC capital increase
that would allow the World Bank affiliate to step up its own
borrowings in private capital markets and keep expanding its
operations over the next five years.
   ---
   COUNTERTRADE: A former senior U.S. Export-Import Bank
official who arranges private countertrade deals between U.S.
companies and others abroad, is trying to persuade U.S.
trade-policy officials to be more supportive of such
transactions.
   Matt Schaffer, of D.M. Schaffer Corp., based in
Washington, says Japanese trading companies have long used
countertrade arrangements that customarily involve payment in
goods, rather than money, for exports.
   Generally, countertrade opponents argue that trading
exports for other goods, ranging from bathtubs to canned
hams, is a burdensome and inefficient way of engaging in
international trade.
   Countertrade used to be a big thing in eastern European
countries, almost as a matter of necessity, but economic
reforms now under way in that part of the world are steering
away from countertrade transactions and U.S. trade-policy
officials have applauded this trend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0024
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0024.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   The Final Plan?
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Soviet Prime Minister Nikolai Ryzhkov is warning that the
Soviet Union will have to cut imports of medicine and
consumer goods sharply; there's no money to pay for them.
Tent cities are popping up in downtown Moscow, part protests,
part Gorbovilles. Rude inspectors at Soviet airports used to
meticulously examine currency exchange forms; now they often
don't bother -- Marlboros, not rubles, have become the
currency of choice. Black markets are taking over goods
distribution.
   In short, the downward spiral of the Soviet Union is
visible everywhere. One prominent Russian academic publicly
calls Gorbachev "our Hitler." That vicious description, while
unfair, reflects broad and deep-seated public bitterness.
Separate articles last week in the Moscow News and literary
Gazette discussed the possibility of a military coup against
the government to restore order.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Gorbachev has followed through on an agreement he made
recently with Boris Yeltsin, throwing his weight behind the
free market reform plan of Stanislav Shatalin. Mr. Shatalin's
plan is a vast improvement on the timid plan written by Mr.
Ryzhkov, which Mr. Gorbachev had heretofore supported. But we
suspect that Mr. Gorbachev did not shift because be's been
spending his evenings reading Adam Smith. In his desperation,
he is willing to back any plan that might help him hold the
crumbling Soviet empire together.
   More important than what the Shatalin plan has to say
about privatization and price reform is the provision that
allows each republic to set its own economic policy. This is
what Mr. Yeltsin and the other republic heads wanted. The
Russian parliament endorsed the Shatalin plan 213-1. As long
as Mr. Gorbachev gives them what they want, they won't have
to set about destroying him. He and the central government
survive another day.
   Mr. Ryzhkov argued that giving the republics independent
economic policy would lead to disintegration. He's probably
right, Mr. Gorbachev can no longer afford to think of the
long term. Even the Shatalin plan has a time schedule of 500
days, an eternity for a system facing imminent collapse.
   Mr. Gorbahev may now be convinced that reform from the
center is impossible. After five years of power, he has shown
himself incapable of producing the necessary transformation.
There is an ineluctable momentum in the Soviet Union toward
decentralized authority. After 70 years of central control,
Soviet peoples want the reverse. This is not only happening
politically but in enterprises and institutions. It brings
disorder and redundancy, as Russians freely admit, but in a
sea of chaos people want control over their own little
islands.
   There simply is no longer an apparatus with the authority
to privatize property on an all-Union level. There is
certainly no authority sophisticated enough to carry out a
privatization scheme that meets various political goals, such
as social equity and fair distribution of property. The
republic governments, where many of the politicians of the
future are already in place, at least have a chance. But
privatization may eventually become simply an ad hoc process
carried out at local levels.
   The shift to the Shatalin plan should cause the West to
rethink its government-to-government transfer programs. If
republics are to become the major economic actors, Westerners
will have to make contacts at that level, and not with the
increasingly redundant central officials. Many in the West
have feared that contact with local officials would be seen
in Moscow as an effort to undermine Mr. Gorbachev. But now
that Mr. Gorbachev himself has signed on to the idea of local
economic independence, he has no grounds to object.
   There have been many Soviet five-year plans since the
Bolshevik revolution. The Shatalin plan may well be the final
economic plan with the word Soviet Union attached. Maybe this
will be the first one to work, or maybe the whirlpool toward
anarchy will swallow it up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International -- Washington Insight:
   Bush's Desire to Peacefully Restrain
   Iraq's Weapons Program May Be Elusive
   ----
   By Roberts S. Greenberger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration says stringent
international controls could peacefully curb Iraq's
biological, chemical and nuclear weapons programs, even if
Saddam Hussein remains in power.
   But judging from recent experience, that may be a pipe
dream.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Baghdad already has the facilities to continue producing
massive quantities of its own biological and chemical
weapons, and it has sophisticated missiles to deliver them,
experts say. More worrisome, the nuclear nonproliferation
treaty can't significantly restrict Saddam Hussein's quest
for nuclear weapons: under the treaty, which Iraq has signed,
he can continue Iraq's nuclear research effort.
   These stark realities fuel the debate over whether the
U.S. can achieve its goals in the Persian Gulf unless it
topples Saddam Hussein.
   So far, the Bush administration hasn't reached its own
conclusion. In his address to a joint session of Congress
last week, the president said only that one long-term U.S.
objective in the Persian Gulf would be "to curb the
proliferation of chemical, biological, ballistic missiles
and, above all, nuclear technologies."
   Lately, the administration seems to be hoping it can
achieve its goal short of eliminating the Iraqi dictator. But
many experts say containment won't work. They note that with
international help, Iraq has built a nearly self-sufficient
defense industry. West German companies built its
chemical-weapons facilities. French companies helped it
construct an electronics plant that makes computer chips and
circuit boards used in air-defense equipment. A Chilean
company designed an Iraqi factory that makes cluster bombs.
   Similarly, Iraq has sophisticated missile technology. In
December, it surprised U.S. and other intelligence services
by launching a rocket capable of putting a satellite in
orbit. And according to a report last week, Iraq successfully
tested an intermediate-range ballistic missile loaded with
chemical weapons.
   "All of our experience over the last decade suggests you
simply cannot effectively control the ability of a country to
obtain technology if they really want to get it," says W.
Seth Carus, research fellow at the Washington Institute for
Near East Policy, a private group.
   The U.S. itself lacks the means to block the flow of
militarily sensitive technology to regional powers. Under
current rules, the Pentagon only has the authority to monitor
certain potentially troublesome exports to communist nations.
But now that the communist bloc has dissolved, it is nations
such as Iraq that pose the greatest threat. Last week, the
Senate passed a measure giving the Pentagon more authority,
but the measure must be reconciled with a House bill.
   Concerning nuclear facilities, Leonard Spector, an expert
on nuclear proliferation issues at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, says the current treaty isn't enough to
safeguard the world against a maverick like Saddam Hussein.
   Non-nuclear countries that have signed the treaty, such as
Iraq, pledge not to develop nuclear weapons. But the treaty
allows them to do nuclear work that ostensibly is for
peaceful purposes. So, Saddam Hussein could continue his
nuclear research program without violating the treaty until
he is just weeks from being able to produce a bomb.
   Mr. Spector says the U.S. prefers additional agreements,
such as one it has with South Korea, that say certain kinds
of nuclear facilities -- such as enrichment plants or large
research reactors -- won't be built even though permitted by
the treaty.
   Last week, Secretary of State James Baker seemed to be
suggesting similar arrangements could be applied in the
Middle East. He told North Atlantic Treaty Organization
allies that the major powers and Mideast nations "need to
consider intrusive, internationally sanctioned measures and
procedures to diminish the threat of Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction."
   But how could "intrusive" measures be peacefully used on
Saddam Hussein? "It seems to me that if Saddam Hussein
withdraws from Kuwait, we're going to be stuck with a
situation where we would wish for more than the treaty, but
won't be able to get it," says Mr. Spector.
   As a result, some experts are concluding reluctantly that
there is only one way to deal effectively with Iraq's nuclear
capabilities. "Given their record on important treaties, we
cannot be sure that their word means they will honor their
obligations," says congressional aide Peter Galbraith, a
Mideast expert. "The only way we can be sure is if their
nuclear facilities are either dismantled or destroyed."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Talks Continue in Tokyo
   On Allied-Signal Dispute
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN ALD
</CO>
<IN>
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- U.S. and Japanese trade negotiators continued
talks over the weekend in an effort to settle a dispute over
whether Allied-Signal Inc. is being denied fair access to the
Japanese market for its amorphous metals material.
   Although the deadline for settling the issue without
formal action by the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative
was technically Saturday, Allied won't be able to activate
its petition until Monday morning in Washington.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official familiar with the talks indicated that,
while there hadn't been any fundamental breakthroughs as of
Sunday morning, there had been enough movement to continue
talking. He rated the chances for an eleventh-hour agreement
as "an even call."
   Allied, based in Morristown, N.J., filed a complaint last
March charging that Japanese electric utilities were delaying
commercial introduction of amorphous-metal electrical
transformers until Japanese steelmakers could find a way
around Allied's Japanese patent protection for the material.
At the request of U.S. trade officials, Allied later
suspended the complaint until Sept. 15 to allow time for the
issue to be settled without formal action.
   Under U.S. trade law, reactivation of the petition could
lead to retaliatory action against Japanese imports to the
U.S. next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0021
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0021.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Kloeckner-Humboldt-Deutz AG:
   German Concern Posts Net,
   Reversing Year-Ago Loss
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   G.KHD
</CO>
<IN>
HEAVY MACHINERY, FARM EQUIPMENT (MAC)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Kloeckner-Humboldt-Deutz AG, a West German engineering and
machinery concern, posted first-half net income of five
million marks ($3.2 million), reversing a year-earlier loss
of 30 million marks.
   World-wide group sales advanced 10% to 1.88 billion marks
from 1.7 billion marks. Year-earlier figures were adjusted
downward to account for shedding operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Amid a far-reaching corporate restructuring, Kloeckner's
return to profitability was apparently aided by the disposal
of some unprofitable businesses in the past 12 months. On the
basis of continuing operations, the company said its five
million-mark profit compared with a year-earlier loss of 18
million marks.
   Kloeckner's order backlog at June 30 increased 22% to 2.08
billion marks.
   For 1990, Kloeckner said it expects "better operating
earnings" than the year-earlier 44 million marks, before
taxes and extraordinary charges, and expressed confidence
about posting net. In 1989, after charges of 194.1 million
marks, the company had a net loss of 170 million marks on
4.06 billion marks of world-wide sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900917-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900917-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Commodities:
   U.S. Pays Record Export Subsidies to Bolster
   Grain Sales to Counter European Competition
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The government has begun paying record
export subsidies to boost U.S. grain sales overseas, but most
analysts say it still won't be enough to shore up sagging
wheat markets.
   The Agriculture Department is going to unprecedented
lengths to counter the competitive challenge of the European
Community at a time of bumper grain crops, swelling
stockpiles and shrinking import demand. For the first time,
so-called export bonuses under the government's Export
Enhancement Program topped $50 a ton last week as Agriculture
Department officials sought to match lavish export subsidies
being offered by the French and other European exporters --
and to protect U.S. market share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "You're looking at record levels," said one official. "I
think we're well into new territory."
   The department, partly in response to political pressure
from the Wheat Belt to do whatever it can to prop up wheat
prices, subsidized the sale of more than 500,000 tons of
wheat last week. Export bonuses on a 100,000-ton sale of hard
red winter wheat to Tunisia averaged a whopping $49.23 a ton,
while bonuses on a 12,000-ton wheat sale to West African
nations averaged a record $54.01 a ton.
   Under the Export Enhancement Program, exporters sell U.S.
wheat and other commodities at the world-market price and
collect bonuses in the form of surplus, government-owned
commodities. The bonuses make up the difference between
higher U.S. prices and the world-market prices.
   But several commodity analysts said such bursts of small-
and medium-sized sales will give the depressed futures
markets only a short-term psychological boost. Some faulted
the Agriculture Department for not making aggressive use of
export bonuses sooner.
   "They were very slow in waking up to the fact that it's a
buyer's market," said Katharina Zimmer, a Merrill Lynch
analyst in New York. "They're now doing what they should have
done long ago."
   Until recently, added Anne Frick, a Prudential-Bache
Securities analyst in New York, the bonuses "haven't been
large enough to compete with the EC."
   The gloomy consensus is that it will take a big sale to
shore up the wheat market, and none appears to be imminent.
   "If we did make a relatively large sale -- one million or
two million tons -- that would trigger a rally of 20 cents a
bushel," said Ms. Zimmer. "The price would fall back some,
but it would put a floor under the market."
   This fall, the Soviet Union is expected to resume buying
grain in large quantities. The Soviets have expressed
interest in obtaining $2 billion in U.S. credit, and the Bush
administration has indicated a willingness to extend
export-credit guarantees. Technically, the Soviet Union is
eligible for credit, but the administration has taken the
political stance that Moscow must liberalize Soviet
immigration law to qualify for most-favored-nation status.
   Most analysts believe credit won't be forthcoming for at
least one month, and there isn't any guarantee the Soviets
will use it for wheat purchases. Ms. Zimmer said, "They're
already looking at a lovely wheat crop." Instead, they may be
more interested in buying corn and soybean meal as well as
certain processed foods that would help mollify disgruntled
consumers.
   Lately, the Soviets "haven't been buying anything except
ready-to-eat items that they need to avoid revolution or
anarchy," said John Schnittker, a Washington-based
agricultural consultant. Two such items: chicken legs and
cigarettes.
   The prospect of bumper crops throughout the Northern
Hemisphere and the loss of the Iraqi market due to the
Persian Gulf crisis have battered wheat prices. But
department officials take sharp issue with criticism that
they have "used the EEP program very meekly."
   "We have had {export} initiatives out there," said a
senior official. "It's more a factor of good crops and lower
buying." He said he expects the latest batch of subsidized
sales to be "very beneficial to the export picture at a time
when there hasn't been all that much export activity."
   Meanwhile, a farm-policy showdown is shaping up between
the Bush administration and lawmakers from grain-growing
states. Rep. Dan Glickman, chairman of a House Agriculture
subcommittee, intends to hold hearings, beginning today, on
the possibility of using export bonuses to boost the sale of
wheat flour and other processed foods, and on how much land
wheat farmers should take out of production in 1991.
   The Senate has adopted a bill requiring farmers to idle
15% of their wheat acreage. Mr. Glickman (D., Kan.) has
proposed a similar measure, but it would give farmers the
option of collecting payments for idling an additional 5%.
The administration has consistently opposed acreage
reductions of this size, arguing that they encourage farmers
overseas to plant more.
   Prudential-Bache's Ms. Frick, said that a 15% reduction,
if enacted, "would give the market a slight short-term boost;
it wouldn't fix the problem."
   Looking ahead to other commodity markets this week:
                                                                                                       

   Precious Metals
                                                                                                       

   Gold prices firmed slightly Friday on heightened Persian
Gulf tensions; the nervousness is expected to continue this
week.
   Traders bought contracts after it was reported that Iraqi
soldiers had broken into a number of foreign embassies in
Kuwait City and that a U.S. naval vessel fired a warning shot
before boarding an Iraqi ship.
   December gold rose only $2.20 an ounce to $391; while
silver and platinum declined. The lack of significant
response to the Middle Eastern developments was due to
traders' ambivalence, one analyst said.
   "There have been a number of weekends when traders have
gone away expecting that fighting would break out in the
Persian Gulf and it hasn't," he said. "This has made for
Monday price declines."
   On the other hand, he noted, the situation is explosive
and any developments are likely to boost prices rather than
weaken them. That's why a moderate demand for gold futures
contracts developed, he said. A major factor hampering a
strong rally, he added, is the lack of demand for gold
bullion.
                                                                                                       

   Energy
                                                                                                       

   Headline-driven oil markets got a flurry of new headlines
over the weekend as war in the Persian Gulf seemed more
imminent than ever. The United Nations security council
unanimously condemned Iraq's raids against French, Canadian,
Dutch, and Belgian embassy compounds in Kuwait. President
Bush appeared on Iraqi television to say that country stands
"on the brink of war" because of its Aug. 2 invasion of
Kuwait.
   In response, the Iraqis called the U.S. leader a liar and
vowed to fight him and his allies, many of whom increased
military and financial support of the U.S. stand against Iraq
following the embassy assaults. Secretary of State James
Baker returned to Washington after raising some $14 billion
for use in the Middle East crisis.
   The heightened Gulf tensions will doubtlessly continue to
push crude oil futures skyward, as they have for the past six
weeks. Trading early in the week should reveal whether a
recent slackening in petroleum product futures prices is
continuing. Some traders had attributed the weakness to
technical factors, but others took note of recent reports
from the U.S. Energy Department and the American Petroleum
Institute that showed increases in petroleum product
inventories. The weekly report from the API, due tomorrow,
will be scrutinized for more evidence that product stocks are
growing.

   Livestock and Meats
                                                                                                       

   A surge in hog and pork belly futures prices last week
makes analysts optimistic about pork's prospects this week,
with strong cash prices for pork likely to continue to
support futures prices. Analysts said cash prices rose
because of competitive bidding among meatpackers for supplies
for slaughter. A larger-than-expected movement of pork
bellies out of cold storage also exerted upward pressure on
prices.
   Also affecting the market last week were rumblings that
the U.S. may be planning a food aid package to the Soviet
Union, and analysts said such speculation may remain in the
market this week. "Traders are trying to make something out
of the meeting between President Bush and {Soviet President
Mikhail} Gorbachev," one analyst said. "Personally, I think
they had other things to talk about than food aid."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
